					   <h3>WRITING ENGINEERING COMPETENCY CLAIMS</h3>
					   <h4 class="kao">About the Competencies</h4>
					   <p>The 2012 Australian Engineering Competency Standards Stage 2 has stated three major occupational categories, which are Engineering Associate, Engineering Technologist, and Professional Engineer. Each of these categories consist sixteen elements of competence which is further divided into four different principal units:</p>
					   <p>- Personal commitment</p>
					   <p>- Value in the workplace</p>
					   <p>- Obligation to community</p>
					   <p>- Technical proficiency</p>
					   <p>Each element of competence provides multiple indicators of attainment that serves as a guide to the engineering work likely to be considered as demonstrating attainment of that competence</p>
					   <p>Applicants are required to prepare an Engineering Competency Claim (ECC) for all the competency standards. You need to prove your competence in each practise area you are seeking registration or chartered in. Prepare an account of your plan of actions and decisions taken for each ECC in any individually verified episodes of engineering, including evidence of your personal competence in the element you picked. You must remember, all these actions need to be verifiable, specific and actual not just statements that include generic principles or behaviour.</p>
					   <p>The evidence you will write must be enough to showcase your competence for a particular ECC in all aspects of ‘what this element means in practice’ (as mentioned in the 2nd column of the tables in the Stage 2 Competency Standards applicable to your occupational category).</p>
					   <p>The Stage 2 Competency Standards mention the Indicators of Attainment for each element (provided in the 3rd column of the tables). These elements majorly serve as a guide related to your engineering work, which demonstrates your competence in any particular element.</p>
					   <p>When it comes to Engineering Problems & Engineering Activities, you must mention personal experience that consist of some or all the characteristics of the related Engineering activities and Engineering problems, as stated in the Stage 2 Competency Standards.</p>
					   <p class="cenb"><i>You must present 3 strong evidences referenced in each of the competency as well as the answers to back up how you achieve the competency with the task carried out during the projects.</i></p>
					   <h3>2- Writing ECCs</h3>
					   <h4 class="kao"> 2.1 Preparation</h4>
					   <p>You develop your capability (competence) through experience and interactions with others. Hark back to your career to date and pen down five of six episodes that helped you grow and which you made significant contributions to.</p>
					   <p>Make your notes as detailed as the descriptions of engineering activities and engineering problems in the Stage 2 Competency Standards.</p>
					   <p>These notes can be created with the help of the material you have contributed to, such as proposals, design reports, specifications, project appraisals, and your resume. Recognize others' contributions and distinguish contributions you believe you made as a result of discussions or collaboration with others. At this point, you should expect your notes to be three or four pages long. Print it and be prepared to make notes on it.</p>
					   <p>Now consider the skills you used in each of these career episodes. At this stage, you should go over the sixteen Elements of Competence. Refer to the Attainment Indicators, as they help you understand the scope anticipated in the corresponding Element. Make a note on your printout for each Element where you believe you have applied the capability described in "what this competence means in practice."</p>
					   <p>Some Elements will be apparent where exactly you have used that capability. In comparison, others may not be very clear. You may discover that you have used certain Elements in all or most of your career episodes. Other Elements may or may not have a showing. If the latter is the case, return to "getting started" and add a career episode in which you used the missing capability.</p>
					   <p>At this stage, choose the experience from your career episodes that best demonstrates your capability in each Element. Choose Wisely! This experience from your career episodes, in particular, will influence the assessors that you have achieved proficiency; that you can practice without supervision, and can assist others in developing this capability.</p>
					   <p>When choosing work experience to provide as evidence of competence, choose contributions to work that have some or all of the characteristics of engineering problems or engineering activities as determined in the competency standard for your occupational category. The following scenarios are provided to help you begin your thinking process.</p>
					   <p class="cenb"><i>"In the new Engineers Australia requirement, all individual attributes within 16 competencies must be addressed. (This is not the same as the previous stage 2). Each competency must have at least three projects referenced, each with an explanation of how the competency was achieved through the work completed/referred to."</i></p>
					   <h4 class="kao"> 2.2 Writing the Claim</h4>
					   <p>Always try to ensure you write the evidence within 700 words per element.</p>
					   <p>Applicants must write credibly proving your abilities contributed to your engineering activity or engineering problem that demonstrate your proficiency in each of the elements of competence.</p>
					   <p>Use active voice and first person like I researched, I did etc. Explain things with utmost precision like what you did, why you did it and how.</p>
					   <p>Make sure that you use the correct grammar and sentences that are well-framed and easy to understand. To list activities, don’t forget to use dot points. Be very clear when explaining any technical terms. Avoid using jargon and make sure the details are verifiable and not hypothetical.</p>
					   <p>Remember that mentioning contributions in any project, program or progress can help you cover various elements. You can even pick a particular career episode to showcase more than one of the elements and make sure you prepare separate narratives for a particular element. Each of these narratives must demonstrate your contribution and your capability in the project. Use can also use examples in each narrative. Mention at least five to six career episodes across the elements.</p>
					   <p>Your ECC must be of 500 words to provide the sufficient evidence, and to prove that you have the relevant competence. Do not just write to meet the word count alone; pay equal attention to provide the sufficient evidence as well as submit enough episodes with relevant material. The official word counter in the eChartered available at the bottom of the claim text box will do the word count for you.</p>
					   <p>Give a brief introduction for each ECC and it must include dates as well as context in which you will prove your claimed competence. Explain your contribution in the project rather than writing just about the project or what the team contributed to accomplish it. Use the correct grammar and write in active voice and in the first person.</p>
