					   <h4 class="kao">Finally, ask yourself this question:</h4>
					   <p class="cenb">Before submitting, ask yourself a question, “Is whatever you have written good enough to prove your competence?” You can also take advice from the experts. You can also use the assessment principles given below:</p>
					   <p><b>- Is it Authentic?</b></p>
					   <p>It must be authentic and explain and prove your personal competency, rather the competence of anyone in the team.</p>
					   <p><b>- Is it Valid?</b></p>
					   <p>It must claim and demonstrate the adequate evidence of the competence proving your abilities in solving any specific situation or problem. Whatever you write should be from your professional experience, not just any hypothetical situation.</p>
					   <p><b>- Is it Reliable?</b></p>
					   <p>You must mention the evidence that proves your credibility against the selected competence and it must be reliable. Do you just write the outcome but write how you accomplish the task? </p>
					   <p><b>- Is it Current?</b></p>
					   <p>You must demonstrate that you are currently competent in the chosen element of competency. Keep in mind that the more recent your evidence is, the more chances you have to prove your competency so make sure the evidence is the latest. Your work experience of the past 8 years should be sufficient to prove all your 16 elements of competence. You can also contact the Assessor if you decide to use the evidence of the past 10 years to know if the experience would be right to use to demonstrate as evidence of your competence.</p>
					   <p><b>- Is it Sufficient?</b></p>
					   <p>It must include enough evidence for the successful assessment of your competence in your occupational category along with the engineering problems and activities that you have dealt with. Make sure you successfully address every aspect of your competence to demonstrate your credibility.</p>
					   <p class="cenb">If the answer is ‘yes’, submit the ECC for verification and assessment.</p>
					   <p>Writing a significant career episode can help you provide the evidence of your competence in several Elements. However, when you claim for all 16 Elements of Competence, the Assessors at EA expect you to provide at least three separate work examples.</p>
